ce:section.ce:para:
Because of the fascinating Raman activity and SERS (surface-enhanced Raman scattering) effect, the graphene oxide and its derivatives are broadly employed in the development of Raman biosensors to detect various biomolecules. Some of the properties include: (1) graphene oxide is Raman active in nature showing two bands at 1350cm−1 (D-band) and 1580cm−1 (G-band), (2) it has the ability to quench the fluorescence properties of many of the fluorophores by FRET mechanism, thus can be employed as better quencher, (3) moreover the GO enhances the Raman signal of an adsorbed Raman reporter via electronic coupling regarded as a chemical enhancement mechanism between the GO and reporters, and the (4) ease of surface modification of the GO with specific probes make the GO and derivatives as a suitable platform for the development of the biosensors (Ling et al., 2015; Xie et al., 2009; Xu et al., 2013). 
                        Kim et al. (2012) developed a hybrid film of GO/polyallylamine-AgNP/polyallylamine-rGO and observed an enhanced SERS effect with highly reproducible SERS signal. Fan et al. (2013) prepared a GO-metal nanoparticle composite and demonstrated an ultrasensitive biosensor (10CFU/mL) for the detection of bacteria. Demeritte et al. developed a GO-conjugated core-shell hybrid material and demonstrated the selective separation and identification of Alzheimer’s disease biomarker from the blood sample. It has also been observed that the hybrid platform able to detect the β-amyloid and Tau protein at very low concentration of 100fg/mL level (Demeritte et al., 2015). Thereafter, GO has been used as the scaffold for the assembly of metal nanoparticles (Au, Ag, etc.) to give a stable SERS hot-spot. The incorporation of the magnetic nanoparticles also makes the GO composite an efficient sensor for the sensitive and rapid detection of bioanalytes. Recently, Liu et al. have prepared a highly effective SERS platform for the detection of the pesticide residues in the fruit peels by adopting the surface magnetic solid phase extraction technique using the Fe3O4@GO@AgNP (Liu et al., 2016). An advanced strategy of this SERS effect has been developed by Duan et al. (2015). They have developed a SERS-based multiplexed DNA detection platform by designing the sandwiched thiolated graphene oxide/plasmonic nanoparticle trilayered composites (Au@Ag-tGO-Au@Ag), followed by coating the nanoparticle surfaces with poly(ethylene glycol). They have successfully demonstrated this trilayered SERS assay combined with magnetic separation make the sensitive, multiplexed detection of DNA sequences of the bacterial pathogens (Fig. 13.8
                        ).
